Lymphangioma; Fuid collection noted near left kidney; Foetal exposure during pregnancy; This observational study case, received on 21-Dec-2020 with processed together received on 29-Dec-2020 from other health professional and concerned a foetus which mother was 28-year-old, female, pregnant subject of body weight: 133 lbs, height: 63.3 inches and body mass index (BMI): 23.3, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study.  The foetus' mother's concurrent conditions included anxiety, acid reflux and morning sickness. The foetus' mother's past medications included Bonjesta (doxylamine succinate, pyridoxine hydrochloride) used for morning sickness, Nexium (esomeprazole) and famotidine, both used for acid reflux. The foetus' mother's concomitant medications included Dexilant (dexlansoprazole), cimetidine and sucralfate for acid reflux, citalopram from anxiety, Phenergan (promethazine) and Zofran (ondansetron) for morning sickness and prenatal plus DHA (unspecified vitamins, docosahexaenoic acid) for pregnancy.  The foetus' mother's obstetrical history included one previous pregnancy with one full term live birth. The foetus' mother had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM). The foetus' mother had no maternal or paternal medical history with MCM. The foetus' mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.   The foetus' mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was reported as 24-Jun-2020. The foetus' mother's estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 31-Mar-2021 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was reported as 01-Apr-2021. The type of pregnancy was singleton. The foetus' father was 32-year-old.   On 25-Aug-2020, the ultrasound scan revealed no MCMs.  On 02-Sep-2020, the counsyl chromosome 13, 18, 21 plus sex chromosome analysis and ultrasound scans revealed no MCMs.  On 12-Oct-2020, at approximately 15 weeks of gestation (calculated per LMP), the foetus' mother was vaccinated with Afluria QIV (Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV) (influenza vaccine; dose, route of administration and anatomical location: not reported) (explicitly coded as 'Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunisation. The batch number reported was P100253284.   On the same day, the maternal serum alpha fetoprotein screening (MSAFP/Serum marker) revealed borderline elevation for spina bifida and it was unknown if MCM was noted.  On 20-Oct-2020, the MSAFP/Serum marker - repeat revealed no MCM.  On 03-Nov-2020, the ultrasound scan revealed partial placenta previa and fluid near left kidney related to baby and no MCMs.  On 01-Dec-2020, the ultrasound revealed MCMs. It was lymphangioma.  The outcome of events lymphangioma and 'perinephric fluid collection' was not reported.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment.  the events lymphangioma and 'perinephric fluid collection' were considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus' Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  The case is linked to 202005981, the corresponding mother case.  Company comment: Lymphangioma and perinephric fluid collection have developed after foetal exposure during pregnancy to the suspect product Afluria QIV. Chronology is plausible. As reported, the foetus' mother's (subject) obstetrical history included one previous pregnancy with one full term live birth. The foetus' mother had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM). The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. Lymphangioma was not noted on the ultrasound three weeks after vaccination. Lymphangioma was revealed by ultrasound after approximately 7 weeks. No significant information regarding the medical history and concomitant medications have been reported. With information presented, causality for the events lymphangioma and perinephric fluid collection cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as possible (defaults to related in the safety database for reporting purposes). SYMPTOM_TEXT: Elevated blood glucose readings, beginning 3:00 AM 12/23, fully resolved by 9:00 AM 12/27. Self-managed via humalog insulin injections as necessary. Averaged roughly an additional 8-10 units of humalog insulin a day during this period, which is unusual for me. For reference, last A1c (08/2020) was 6.8. Blood glucose levels during the time mentioned above frequently >300, up to 350-ish. I also noticed that my elevated blood glucose readings required more correctional insulin than usual to address during this time. No illness or symptoms beyond typical dry mouth that accompanies high glucose readings. No call to physician as I was able to manage manually. No impact on my ability to function and perform daily activities, other than the inconvenience of additional insulin injuections. Potentially related to minor changes in activity and eating practices during "holiday" period, but it mirrored blood glucose elevations I've experienced in the past when ill.
LAB_DATA: I use a Dexcom G6 continuous glucose monitor, so I'm not sure how to report this part. As mentioned above, blood glucose readings elevated during this time. I went to bed early at 9:00 pm, with the headache, stomachache, fatigue, and my arm feeling very sore. I slept very restlessly with horrible dreams, as if I were sick or had the flu. In the middle of the night, I'm not sure when, I woke up feeling very achy and sore and freezing cold. After using the bathroom, I passed out, and hit my head on the floor or wall, resulting in a bump/cut. My husband heard me fall and found me lying on the floor.  I kept repeating "help me" and "water", and he was thinking that I would likely need to go to a hospital. He elevated my legs, put an icepack on my head, and got me water, and I became more lucid and started to feel better. I took 2 ibuprofen and drank water, then was able to get back into bed. I was very very cold but at one point woke up sweating. I slept the rest of the night and woke up this morning at 7:00 am (12/31) feeling fine, aside from tiredness, with no temperature.

This patient is a 72 y.o. female presenting to the emergency department with a chief complaint of acute palpitations onset this afternoon. Patient works as a pediatrician and states that after work today she went to receive her COVID-19 vaccine. She reports that about 10 minutes after getting the vaccine, she began to develop a heavy sensation in her chest as well as palpitations. EMS at the vaccine site performed a field EKG which the patient observed to have isolated PVCs. They then obtained a full EKG that again showed isolated PVCs. At this time the patient's blood pressure was taken and recorded to be elevated at 160/110. This caused the patient concern as she has no prior cardiac history or history of hypertension. Patient notes her systolic pressure at baseline is usually 110-120. Following onset patient reached out to her husband's cardiologist, Dr. who recommended she present to the ED as he was unable to see her in his office. Upon arrival to the ED patient reports that the heavy sensation in her chest has resolved, but she still feels "off".

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received my vaccine on December 22nd, 2020 at around 830 Am. That afternoon, about 3 PM, I started to have a reaction. It started with tingling/numbness in my right hand which progressed up my arm into my elbow. About 10 minutes later, it then progressed into my right foot, and my left foot. About 10 minutes after that, I started to get flushed and a neck rash (diagnosed from Dr.). I took Benadryl and Ibuprofen 800mg PO every 6 hours for the next 24 hours. The numbness in my right foot and left foot along with the flushness went away a couple hours later. Although, the numbness in my right hand never went away. It came and went for the next 4 days until December 27th and 28th when it started getting worse. On December 28th evening, it got so bad that I was debating going to the emergency room around 1 am. The numbness and tingling was in my right hand and started shooting up my arm. The nerve pain around my wrist was unbearable. I finally fell asleep and the next morning, it was not nearly as bad, but was still there.  The numbness and tingling moved from my right hand mainly to right hand, right foot, right leg, left foot and left hand today (12-30-2020).
LAB_DATA: My ID docs called a neurologist in our group, Dr. He saw me on December 29th in which he said this could potentially be guillain barre or it could just be a allergy reaction, both due to the covid vaccine. He did a full evaluation and found that I had neuropathic pain in my right hand and right foot. As of the 29th, the numbness and tingling was back to my right foot also and would come and go. He gave me a shot of decadron 1g (even though it would blunt my antibody titer response to the vaccine) and gave me extended release gabapentin to start on the evening of the 29th. He also had me start a Medrol dose pack starting on the 30th (today).   12-30-2020 Dr. did a STAT EMG which came back fairly normal. He can almost definitively say this is not guillain barre although he still concerned about some of the more rare de-myelinating brain disorders caused from vaccines. he said the most likely on the differential is a small fiber peripheral neuropathy stimulated from the lipid moiety that encompasses the messenger RNA of the mRNA vaccine.  He told me to continue the prescribed meds and he is going to do a biopsy on Monday to try to diagnose the small fiber peripheral neuropathy.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I woke up Tuesday, the morning following injection, to get ready for work. I got  my coffee, and felt very lightheaded and fuzzy. I sat down on the bed. Everything began to get dark and fuzzy, I felt like I was going to throw up. I tried to call out for my husband, but I didn't think I got his name out. The next thing I remember my husband was holding my and yelling at me, trying to get me to respond. He reports that he heard me call his name, he came into the bedroom to find me stretched out, stiff as a board, with my head cocked all the way back, tongue sticking out of my mouth, and unresponsive. He picked me up and my body remained rigid. After a minute and a half, I came out of it extremely confused. I did not know where I was or if it was real or a dream. He ran me to the hospital across the street from our house. I was admitted to the ED where I received IV fluids, an EKG, CT scan, and blood work. They do not know why it happened to me, but agreed it was possible I had experienced a seizure in reaction the the vaccine I received less that 24 hours prior.
LAB_DATA: EKG was normal CT scan was normal blood work was normal All done in ED of Hospital on 12/29/2020.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the Moderna vaccine on Dec 28th at 12:15 pm.  I was feeling fine at the time.  At 6:30 pm on the 28th I started to have a severe headache and chills.  Through the night of the 28th and into the 29th,  I developed a fever of 101.7 before I took Tylenol.  I called my dr that said alternate Ibuprofen and Tylenol every 4 hours.  By the 3rd hour each time my fever would climb back to 101.7 and would never be lower than 100.3. On the 29th, I had a severe headache, severe joint pain to the point I could barely turn in pain, severe chills, severe muscle aches, very weak to the point I had to be helped to the bathroom, no appetite, dizziness, some confusion, very weak and felt at times I could not walk as the day progressed (maybe weakness).  My fever and other symptoms continued through the night.  I saw the dr. on the 30th - severe headache, fevers without Ibuprofen 101.3-101.7, severe muscle aches, severe joint pain throughout, dizziness, sore throat, chills.  I started on steroids and continued with Ibuprofen and had chills and drenching chills, slight shortness of breath that continued through the night, fever of 100.3, dizziness, sore throat, severe headache, severe muscle and joint pain.  On the 31st, I have a fever of 100, some chills, severe joint pain, muscle aches, very bad headache, increasing very sore throat and now losing my voice and severe headache.  I was home throughout the holiday with just my children, no visitors, no activities outside the home.  Children are home schooled.  Masks and visors worn at work, all visitors and staff wear masks.  Groceries are no-touch pick up.  No known exposures  Symptoms after vaccine were worse than actual covid, had to miss work and still feel very bad. Was unable to care for my children and barely able to care for myself after the vaccine, unlike when I had covid - I could still function.  Unsure if I should have waited longer to receive the vaccine than right after I was just feeling better.  Feeling very ill again with symptoms
LAB_DATA: saw Dr on Dec 30th  - started me on steroids - other illnesses ruled out - no ear, nose, sinus issues, no flu, no strep throat

Patient arrived at observation parking lot at approximately 10:55 after receiving COVID-19 Vaccine to left upper arm. Patient was stopped by observation staff and asked about any previous history of anaphylaxis. Patient denied. Patient was instructed to remain in line for 15 observation period and was instructed to set timer to phone and honk if she experienced any adverse reactions. Patient got in line.  At approximately 11:00, patient honked horn. This nurse and one other nurse ran to vehicle. Patient was waving arm out of the window. Other nurse instructed to call for help and this nurse assessed patient. Patient stated ?I don?t feel good. My throat feels weird. I think it?s closing.? Initial vital sign were HR-85 and Pulse ox 98%.  1103-This nurse gave initial dose of epi to R Outer Thigh. 911 called by other staff.  1105-20G IV started to LAC.  1107-O2 given at 3L via nasal cannula. 50 mg Benadryl given via IV. Lost IV access after medication administration due to rain and being unable to secure line.  1108-2nd IV attempt was unsuccessful to LUA. 1111-O2 90%. Non rebreather applied and O2 bumped to 50L. Surgical mask applied over non rebreather. 1111-2nd dose of Epi given to R outer thigh. 1112-BP-160/70. Fire arrived on scene. 1113- 3rd IV attempt to RIJ was unsuccessful.  1116- 20G IV to R hand successful with flush.  1120- NS initiated.  1121-BP- 160/84. 1122-EMS arrived. 1126-Patient loaded into ambulance. 1131- Patient left via ambulance.  Patient was alert and responsive through the entire ordeal. Patient was able to answer questions. Patient expressed relief from throat swelling after initial Epi. Pupils equal and reactive. Patient stated, ?I feel better. My throat is dry, and I feel sleepy.? Patient vocalized pain from IV attempts. After 2nd dose of Epi, patient?s hands were cold to touch and VS were not able to be read from pulse ox. Pulse obtained via palpation. Pulse was 52 after all medication administration by staff. Patient reported taking Zyrtec and duloxetine prior to coming for vaccine today. Denies any history of anaphylaxis. Patient requested this nurse call her husband. Husband notified of event per patient request.
OTHER_MEDS: Zyrtec Duloxetine Unknown monthly injection for residual brain tumor

35 y.o. year-old female RN that presented to the clinic today for a Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19  vaccine.  Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19  vaccine was administered at: Time: 0852 Date: 12/31/2020  Patient presented with symptoms at time 0905 while being observed following vaccine.  Patient's symptoms include the following:  Skin and Mucosal symptoms: No  Respiratory Symptoms: Yes: Sensation of throat closing.  If described on scale of 1-10 with throat closure being a 10, stated "throat closure could feel like a 2-3 on 1-10 scale.  Symptoms also described as "scratchy throat". She hadn't had any breakfast today.    She reported history of reaction after pneumococcal ppsv 23 vaccine which consisted of very red, sore, swollen arm with fever following vaccine.  Reported to healthcare provider who let her know she "suffered an allergic reaction to one or more components of the pneumococcal vaccine and not just side effects".  She was treated with ibuprofen, ice, and advised to take zyrtec, allegra, or benadryl.  She reports she took benadryl and never required any epinephrine.  She denied any shortness of breath, difficulty breathing, or swelling of the face, mouth, or throat with that reaction.    She does report a possible reaction to bees/wasps for which she felt previous tingling in the lips, but when reviewed with her PCP, they opted to not order epi pen for her use at the time.  She denies ever needing epinephrine or epi pen use in the past that she is aware of.   Gastrointestinal Symptoms: No  Cardiovascular: Yes: Dizziness  The following actions were performed: Patient was brought to exam room to lie down Feet were elevated Given some water  Given some juice Vital signs: @0915 BP 130/85, Pulse 84, Oxygen on room air 100%, Temp 98.8 F, @0923 BP 126/85, Pulse 75, Oxygen on room air 100%  Airway, Breathing, Circulation, and level of consciousness assessed and normal Bendaryl 50mg administered as a single dose   Patient reported dizziness was resolved quickly after lying down.  She stated her "throat closure" symptoms were also improved.  She drank water, apple juice, and had 2 saltine crackers without incident.    Airway, Breathing, Circulation normal throughout assessment period.  Vital signs again checked at 0945:  BP 135/85, Pulse 80, Oxygen 100%, Temp. 98.9 F.  Discussed normal adverse events following this vaccine with patient.  Also discussed more severe adverse events which can include difficulty breathing, swelling of face/throat, fast heartbeat, bad rash all over body, and dizziness or weakness.  Discussed she could take another dose of benadryl if she was concerned about any continued, mild swelling of throat in 4-6 hours.   If she has severe swelling of face/throat that is worsening or not resolved with benadryl, she should call 9-1-1 immediately.  She voiced understanding.  We discussed that she would need to weigh the benefits/risks of a 2nd dose, and if she does choose to get a 2nd dose based on a minor reaction not causing severe anaphylaxis, she would need to make sure staff are prepared with benadryl and epinephrine to be used if needed.  She voiced understanding.  Her husband was notified and he came and picked her up after she was observed for an additional 30 minutes in the observation area outside the clinic.  She left the observation area at 1016.
OTHER_MEDS: Tylenol, Albuterol, Buspar, Vitamin D3, Voltaren, Benadryl, Cymbalta, Folvite, Humira, Mobic, Methotrexate, Prednisone,

There was no previous temperature excursion. Digital Data Logger was involved.  There were no adverse experiences to report as a result of the temperature excursion.

No additional AE; multiple temperature excursions/multiple doses of ROTATEQ were administered to multiple patients; This spontaneous report was received from an office administrator referring to an infant female patient of unknown age. Information regarding the patient's pertinent medical history, historical drugs, concurrent conditions, concomitant therapies, and previous drug reactions or allergies was not reported.      On 08-NOV-2020, the patient was vaccinated with an improperly stored dose of rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ) lot # 1661000, expiration date 13-MAY-2021, at a dose of 2 milliliter once, orally for prophylaxis. SYMPTOM_TEXT: This patient reports being in his normal good state of health other than reporting a viral like symptoms 1 week prior to receipt of the influenza vaccination that had resolved the day he was given his annual influenza vaccine on 10/22/2019.  He reported no adverse reactions until day 2-3 post vaccination when first experienced commonly reported vaccine adverse events of generalized pain, arthralgia, tingling (face, lips, throat, arms, legs, back of throat), bifacial weakness of legs, and tightness in throat, and fatigue.  However the progression of his symptoms over the next 2 weeks of worsening total body pain, paresthesia, headaches, bilateral weakness first to lower then upper extremities (upward progression), tightness in his throat, difficulty swallowing, difficulty with speech, difficulty-inability to stand-walk-run, bowel incontinence, chest pressure and shortness of breath, are not typical vaccine reactions.  A comprehensive medical record review identified on 11/7/2019 a lumbar puncture that showed elevated CSF proteins confirming the diagnosis of axonal Guillain Barre Syndrome for which he received intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG). Following his initial admission, he spent the next 3 months in rehab, being readmitted to the hospital x3 for relapsing symptoms that required further treatment with IVIG and plasmapheresis. Following each treatment his symptoms markedly improved until he was finally able to return home 20 January 2020 to continue with home physical therapy. In January 2020 he was given a diagnosis of Chronic Inflammatory Demyelinating Polyradiculoneuropathy (CIDP) as his symptoms persisted greater than 8 weeks which is the characteristic for this diagnosis.  He has been working under light duty profile since January 2020 and remains under the care of Dr. for plasmapheresis therapy every 3-4 weeks.
LAB_DATA: x-rays head, spine w/CT, MRI, LP, labs, EKG, EMG/neuro studies and more
OTHER_MEDS: 10/31/2019: On no medication 1/20/2020: gabapentin 600 mg TID,

I am a physician who received Covid vaccine on Thursday morning 12/17.  Over the proceeding 24-48 hours, I developed mild headache and fatigue to extent napped Saturday.  Tuesday 12/22 developed muscle soreness right buttock radiating behind left knee and intermittently down to left heal, and a sensitivity to touch behind that leg.  I thought I was developing sciatica. Muscle aches and sensitivity worsened and was having aching with intermittent shooting pains in pelvis and both legs to extent worked standing up.  No weakness, change in bowel or bladder. Christmas eve late afternoon, developed severe headache, body aches limited to pelvis and below, and extreme sensitivity to skin (painful to sit on toilet).  Headache was so severe I vomited sick times and contemplated going to ER as concerned about meningitis.  Also with fever. I have a history of csf leak repaired via laminectomy in 2015 and have never been as sick as I was Christmas even overnight.  By Friday afternoon able to get out of bed and alternate ibuprofen/tylenol. Headache became less severe with mild body aches limited to lower body and symptoms persisted days. Sunday, temp still elevated at 101.5, the Monday 100.2, Tuesday 99.4, and Weds 12/30 97.4 and finally back to baseline.  I had a negative Covid rapid antigen test Sat 12/26 at 4pm and another neg Covid pcr test Monday afternoon 12/28.  Other than fatigue, I am back to baseline.  I would like guidance regarding whether to proceed with 2nd dose as I am very concerned I experienced aseptic meningitis.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine.  1-2 minutes after receiving vaccine, I experienced light-headedness, dizziness, and a heavy feeling in my head. I relayed my symptoms to the RN who administered the vaccine and told her I did not feel well enough or safe enough to walk down the hall to the observation room. She got me water, orange juice, and a breakfast bar. I finished the breakfast bar and drank part of the water and orange juice. She told me to stay seated with her for as long as I felt necessary. 15 minutes later, the same RN told me I was ashen pale. She advised me to lie on the floor, which I did with my feet up on a chair. 15-30 minutes later, I told her I felt well enough to walk. She told me to do so and I sat with the person who came with me to receive the vaccine as well. We talked for about 15 minutes when I told her I felt numbness, tingling, and a burning sensation in my throat and the back of my tongue. She got an MD who walked me to another room to quickly examine me. I told her my symptoms and started to experience mild nausea that lasted about 5 minutes. She hooked me up to a machine which revealed 99% O2 sat and heart rate 72. She gave me Pepcid PO. I waited another 30 minutes and told her I felt well enough to leave. As I was driving home, I called the MD who examined me after vaccine administration and reported redness and sores at the back of my throat and back of tongue. I also reported the same burning, tingling, and burning sensation in the back of my throat and back of tongue. She advised me to go to the employee health clinic and be seen by an MD. I arrived at the clinic 15 minutes later. Vital signs were taken with blood pressure in the 140?s systolic, an O2 sat of 100%, and heart rate of 76. The MD who examined me stated this was probably some type of allergic reaction to the vaccine. He gave me a steroid shot IM, Benadryl 25 mg PO and had me stay 90 minutes to be observed after administration. I felt well enough to go home. He told me to take Pepcid PO BID and Benadryl 25 mg q 4-6 hours for the next 1-2 days. He also wrote a prescription for a Medrol Dose Pack to be taken in 2 days if symptoms did not abate. He advised me to go immediately to the ER if I had difficulty breathing where epinephrine could be given. I stated agreement and went home. At home I continued to have sores, redness, tingling, and a burning sensation in my throat and on my tongue as well my head feeling heavy. I also felt muscle soreness and a burning sensation in from my feet to my knees in my legs bilateral. I took the Benadryl and Pepcid as directed and went to bed.  The 2nd day, I still felt the odd burning sensation in my throat and on my tongue as well as the presence of sores in the same area. I also had a heavy feeling in my head, felt woozy intermittently, and had a burning sensation with itchiness on my chin. I picked up the Medrol Dose Pack to have on hand in case I needed. I continued to take the Benadryl and Pepcid as directed by the MD. The 3rd day, the numbness, burning sensation on my tongue and throat is gone but the burning, itching sensation on my chin persists. Sores are still present on the back of my tongue and the back of my throat along with redness. I still have an intermittent feeling of heaviness in my head. I continue to take Pepcid but have stopped taking Benadryl. I have decided not to take the Medrol Dose Pack. I have decided to let the symptoms run their course and call a doctor if any symptoms change in severity or go to the ER if I experience a medical emergency.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin D, B Complex, Multi-Vitamin, Vitamin B-12, Flax Seed Oil

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Immediate onset of anterior chest tightness and sensation of throat closing/fullness; tachycardia. Nursing reported "SVT" on ECG and then sent her to our clinic as one of our docs is her PCP. Her ECG was clearly not SVT, showing 1 PVC and heart rate of 85 and 97 on 2 separate tracings. No labs or meds given on either ED visit.

Received Moderna CoVid vaccine today around 220.  Began to feel symptoms at approx 230  Symptoms include itching at site of injection R arm, then generalized itching, then lips felt tingly and itchy.  Nurse stat called overhead.  Patient told doctor that within minutes of receiving the vaccine, she had erythema and pruritus at the injection site on the right deltoid.  She then started having pruritus of the lips and face.  Vital signs were obtained.  All vitals were within normal limits.  Lung exam and heart exam were performed.  Patient had good air movement and no wheezes on lung exam.  Oxygenating at 100%.  Heart exam was within normal limits.  Patient was given 50 mg of Benadryl for the mild reaction.  She was transported to the observation room in primary care to be monitored more thoroughly.  Approximately 40 minutes after having the COVID vaccine and approximately 30 minutes after having Benadryl, patient's symptoms worsened.  Her erythema and swelling of her lips and face worsened.  Exam was consistent with angioedema of the lips.  Patient reported tingling in her throat.  Due to this worsening and Benadryl already on board, epinephrine was given in the left lateral thigh by the RN.  Due to needing epinephrine, 3099 was contacted.  Discussed case with them.  Patient is not a member.  Recommended direct call to 911 for ambulance transfer to the emergency department.  This was discussed with the patient.  She is comfortable with this decision.  EMS arrived.  Please see RN note for exact time.  Handout was given to EMS.  Patient was transported out of facility.  At time of transfer she was alert, oriented, and in no distress.

Patient started having myalgia, chills, nausea on the next day of the vaccination. on 2nd day (12/29) patient had chest pressure which made her present to Hospital ED. She had troponin elevation to 1.14. Cardiac Catheterization was done which was negative. On Trans Thoracic Echocardiogram, patient was found to have hypokinesis of the mid and distal segment with some sparing of apex proving Takotsubo (stress induced) cardiomyopathy. Patient did not have any underlying  emotional or physical stress going on in her life or family. Till now extensive infectious as well as inflammatory work up is done to rule out any secondary causes of cardiomyopathy which till date have remained negative.  As a diagnosis of exclusion, her presentation seems to be COVID-19 vaccine induced Takotsubo Cardiomyopathy
LAB_DATA: TTE 12/30: EF 35%. Regional variation with normal contraction at the base and hypokinesis of the mid and distal segments with perhaps some sparing of the apex. Pattern is consistent with Takotsubo cardiomyopathy.  Cardiac Catheterization 12/30: Mild Coronary Disease in LAD. Otherwise minimal CAD. Mildly elevated left sided filling pressure.  ESR: 24 CRP <5 WBC 6.46, H/H 13.7/39.7

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Over 24 hours after the vaccine I developed fatigue which I thought was normal - around 1pm the day after the vaccine. I ate some crackers and rested.   At 4pm I started to feel bloated and heart burn, the heart burn turned to stomach pain with some pain in my back as well.  I took1  pepcid and a digestive enzyme around 5pm but the bloating, heart burn and stomach pain got worse. I took a tylenol about 30 minutes later.  The abdominal pain and abdominal distension continued to get worse (although the heart burn subsided) and at 7pm I was lieing on the floor near the bathroom. The abdominal pain and distension continued to get worse and then nausea set in.  When the nausea came on stronger I took pepto bismol. Around 8pm, I took half the normal dosage and the nausea and pain improved slightly, then the nausea came back and I took another half dosage at 9:00. The nausea and pain continued and I took another half dose at 10pm and then again at 11pm.  At 10pm I was able to lie in bed instead of on the floor by the toilet. By 12am  I was able to fall asleep (I normally go to sleep at 9pm). In the morning when I woke up the nausea and pain were gone.  Today I still have moderate fatigue but no abdominal pain at this time.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Fever, chills, and severe fatigue lasting 12 hours

Patient reports first noticing that her back was itchy around 8pm on 12/30/2020, approximately 9hrs post vaccination. She asked her husband to scratch her back and when doing so, he noticed red and raised welts on her back. Upon waking this morning, the red, raised, and itchy rash had spread from her back to the rest of her body and is now on her back, chest, abdomen, arms, hands, neck, face, legs, and feet. No rash on palms or soles. Skin lesions examined and are consistent with urticaria. She has taken a total of 3 doses of hydroxyzine 25mg without any improvement. Patient also applied OTC 1% hydrocortisone cream which provided some slight, temporary relief. The only other treatment tried was a cool compress with witch hazel and this was also soothing.   Patient's husband informed her that he noted "red splotches" on her back the morning of 12/30/2020 prior to vaccination but didn't think much of it. Her symptoms obviously significantly worsened later that day. However, given that she had atypical symptoms prior to vaccination she is questioning whether this is truly related to the vaccine. She denies any other new exposures prior to symptom onset. No new soaps, lotions, detergents, foods, etc. The only thing she can think of is that in the past she has developed puffiness under her eyes and a runny nose when in the vicinity of marijuana. She inadvertently came in contact with a parcel that likely contained marijuana at work the night before she was vaccinated. Patient denies any previous skin rash due to marijuana exposure but wonders if this could have contributed to her current symptoms.   She denies shortness of breath, wheezing, tachycardia, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, or swelling of face/lips. Patient states that other than the diffuse itchy rash, "I feel fine."   June does have a history of significant oral swelling and breathing difficulty following bee sting in the past. For this reason, she does carry an EpiPen with her at all times. She has never been evaluated by an allergy specialist but has history of severe reactive airway disease when exposed to perfume. Will refer to allergy specialist for further allergy testing.   Today in clinic, patient was administered 50mg IM Benadryl and she was prescribed famotidine 20mg BID to take at home in addition to Benadryl 25mg TID prn. She felt the witch-hazel provided more relief than the hydrocortisone cream so she will continue this with cool compress or cool showers prn. Follow up next week for recheck.
